Japan, China, Philippines, Malaysia, India: Asia Bonds, Currency Preview

-- B y   A n i l   V a r m a
-- 
2011-05-24T22:19:26Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-24/japan-china-philippines-malaysia-india-asia-bonds-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in  Asia ’s bonds and currencies
today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the previous
trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan : Chief Cabinet Secretary Yukio Edano will hold media
briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  The  Bank of Japan  will release at 8:50 a.m. minutes of its
April 28 board meeting. Governor Masaaki Shirakawa will speak at
an economic forum at 12:30 p.m.  The Ministry of Finance will release at 8:50 a.m. the trade
balance data for April. The trade deficit was 703.7 billion yen
($8.6 billion) last month, according to economists surveyed by
Bloomberg News. The ministry will announce at 10:30 a.m. the
amount of 10-year  government bonds  it plans to sell in June.  The yield on the 1.1 percent government bond maturing in
March 2021 was at 1.12 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading
Co. The yen traded at 82.04 as of 7:15 a.m. in Tokyo.  China : The government will auction 30 billion yuan ($4.6
billion) of 50-year debt.  The yield on the 3.83 percent bond due March 2021 was 3.83
percent, according to Chinabond, the nation’s biggest debt-
clearing house. The yuan was at 6.4986.  India : The government plans to raise 110 billion rupees
($2.4 billion) selling 91- and 182-day treasury bills.  The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due April 2021 was 8.37
percent. The rupee was at 45.215.  Malaysia: The government will sell a combined 2 billion
ringgit ($655 million) of 180- and 364-day notes.  The yield on the benchmark 4.16 percent bond due July 2021
was at 4.03 percent. The ringgit was at 3.0530.  Philippines : The statistics office will report on the
nation’s trade balance for March. The country had a deficit of
$823 million in February.  The yield on the 6.50 percent bond due April 2021 was 6.45
percent, according to Tradition Financial Services. The peso was
at 43.395 per dollar.  Thailand: The government will auction 8 billion baht ($263
million) of bonds maturing in 2014.  The yield on the 3.125 percent debt due December 2015 was
3.45 percent. The baht was at 30.41 per dollar.  To contact the reporter on this story:
